            <p>J. SOLIS&#45;COHEN&#44; M.D.&#44; 431 Walnut St.<lb/>
                OFFICE HOURS&#58; 9 to 11 A.M.&#44; 4 to 5 P.M.<lb/></p>
            <p>Philadelphia&#44; Oct 21 1880<lb/></p>
            <p>Revd &#38; Dear Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>It is several<lb/> days since I rec&#39;d a note from<lb/> brother Solomon concerning &#91;&#63;&#93;&#44;<lb/> but I&#39;ve been so occupied as thro&#39;<lb/> forgetfulness to neglect it.  Todd is<lb/> hardly a suitable subject to practice<lb/> medicine&#44; and a position as muse<lb/> would be no step forward&#8212;rather<lb/> the reverse.  At Jefferson Hospital<lb/> we take none but acute cases&#44; &#38;<lb/> require skilled nurses&#44; added to<lb/> which&#44; there is rarely a vacancy.<lb/>  At the German Hospital&#44; a German<lb/> is requisite&#44; &#38; there is no vacancy<lb/> there at present.  Were Todd&#39;s<lb/> appearance more presentable<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>I might make an effort&#44; at your<lb/> desire&#44; to give him a position in<lb/> my own house as office attend&#45;<lb/>ant&#44; but he is unfortunately<lb/> calculated to deter patients rather<lb/> than attract them.  I&#39;m sorry for<lb/> him.  If you want a five dollar<lb/> bill for him at any time I<lb/> will gladly aid you to that extent<lb/> provided my name is not mentioned<lb/></p>
            <p>Im yrs truly<lb/>
                J Solis Cohen<lb/></p>
            <p>Revd S. Morais<lb/></p>
        </body>
    </text>
